\fs20 6.300 Scope of subpart.\

\f1\b0 This subpart prescribes policies and procedures, and identifies the statutory authorities, for contracting without providing for full and open competition.\

\f0\b 6.301 Policy.\

\f1\b0 (a) \cf3 41 U.S.C.3304 \cf4 and \cf3 10 U.S.C. 3204 \cf4 each authorize, under certain conditions, contracting without providing for full and open competition. The Department of Defense, Coast Guard, and National Aeronautics and Space Administration are subject to \'93 \cf3 10 U.S.C. 3204\cf4 . Other executive agencies are subject to \cf3 41 U.S.C.3304\cf4 . Contracting without providing for full and open competition or full and open competition after exclusion of sources is a violation of statute, unless permitted by one of the exceptions in \cf3 6.302\cf4 .\
(b) Each contract awarded without providing for full and open competition shall contain a reference to the specific authority under which it was so awarded. Contracting officers shall use the U.S. Code citation applicable to their agency. (See \cf3 6.302\cf4 .)\
(c) Contracting without providing for full and open competition shall not be justified on the basis of-\
(1) A lack of advance planning by the requiring activity; or\
(2) Concerns related to the amount of funds available (
\f2\i e.g., 
\f1\i0 funds will expire) to the agency or activity for the\
acquisition of supplies or services.\
(d) When not providing for full and open competition, the contracting officer shall solicit offers from as many potential\
sources as is practicable under the circumstances.\
(e) For contracts under this subpart, the contracting officer shall use the contracting procedures prescribed in \cf3 6.102\cf4 (a) or\
(b), if appropriate, or any other procedures authorized by this regulation.\

