\f0\b\fs20 13.000 Scope of part.\

\f1\b0 This part prescribes policies and procedures for the acquisition of supplies and services, including construction, research and development, commercial products, and commercial services, the aggregate amount of which does not exceed the simplified acquisition threshold (see \cf3 2.101\cf4 ). \cf3 subpart 13.5 \cf4 provides special authority for acquisitions of commercial products and commercial services exceeding the simplified acquisition threshold but not exceeding $7.5 million ($15 million for acquisitions as described in \cf3 13.500 \cf4 (c)), including options. See \cf3 part 12 \cf4 for policies applicable to the acquisition of commercial products and commercial services exceeding the micro-purchase threshold. See \cf3 36.602-5 \cf4 for simplified procedures to be used when acquiring architect-engineer services.\

\f0\b 13.001 Definitions.\

\f1\b0 As used in this part-\

\f2\i Authorized individual 
\f1\i0 means a person who has been granted authority, in accordance with agency procedures, to acquire supplies and services in accordance with this part.\

\f2\i Governmentwide commercial purchase card 
\f1\i0 means a purchase card, similar in nature to a commercial credit card, issued to authorized agency personnel to use to acquire and to pay for supplies and services.\

\f2\i Imprest fund 
\f1\i0 means a cash fund of a fixed amount established by an advance of funds, without charge to an appropriation, from an agency finance or disbursing officer to a duly appointed cashier, for disbursement as needed from time to time in making payment in cash for relatively small amounts.\

\f2\i Third party draft 
\f1\i0 means an agency bank draft, similar to a check, that is used to acquire and to pay for supplies and services. (See Treasury Financial Management Manual, Section 3040.70.)\

\f0\b 13.002 Purpose.\

\f1\b0 The purpose of this part is to prescribe simplified acquisition procedures in order to-\
(a) Reduce administrative costs;\
(b) Improve opportunities for small, small disadvantaged, women-owned, veteran-owned, HUBZone, and service-disabled\
veteran-owned small business concerns to obtain a fair proportion of Government contracts; (c) Promote efficiency and economy in contracting; and\
(d) Avoid unnecessary burdens for agencies and contractors.\

\f0\b 13.003 Policy.\

\f1\b0 (a) Agencies shall use simplified acquisition procedures to the maximum extent practicable for all purchases of supplies or services not exceeding the simplified acquisition threshold (including purchases at or below the micro-purchase threshold). This policy does not apply if an agency can meet its requirement using-\
(1) Required sources of supply under \cf3 part 8 \cf4 (
\f2\i e.g., 
\f1\i0 Federal Prison Industries, Committee for Purchase from People Who are Blind or Severely Disabled, and Federal Supply Schedule contracts);\
(2) Existing indefinite delivery/indefinite quantity contracts; or\
(3) Other established contracts.\
(b) (1) Acquisitions of supplies or services that have an anticipated dollar value above the micro-purchase threshold,\
but at or below the simplified acquisition threshold, shall be set aside for small business concerns (see \cf3 19.000\cf4 , \cf3 19.203\cf4 , and subpart \cf3 19.5\cf4 ).\
(2) The contracting officer may make an award to a small business concern under the-\
(i) 8(a) Program (see subpart \cf3 19.8\cf4 );\
(ii) Historically Underutilized Business Zone (HUBZone) Program (but see \cf3 19.1305 \cf4 );\
(iii) Service-Disabled Veteran-Owned Small Business (SDVOSB) Program (see subpart \cf3 19.14\cf4 ); or (iv) Women-Owned Small Business (WOSB) Program (see \cf3 subpart 19.15\cf4 ).\
(3) The following contracting officer\'92s decisions for acquisitions at or below the simplified acquisition threshold are not subject to review under subpart \cf3 19.4\cf4 :\
(i) A decision not to make an award under the 8(a) Program.\
(ii) A decision not to set aside an acquisition for HUBZone small business concerns, service-disabled veteran-owned small business concerns, or EDWOSB concerns and WOSB concerns eligible under the WOSB Program.\
(4) Each written solicitation under a set-aside shall contain the appropriate provisions prescribed by part \cf3 19\cf4 . If the solicitation is oral, however, information substantially identical to that in the provision shall be given to potential quoters.\

